172
0:07:26.34,000 --> 0:07:29,000
The second thing is the sense of smell.

173
0:07:29.922,000 --> 0:07:32,000
Each of us has a unique odor world,

174
0:07:33.391,000 --> 0:07:35,000
in the sense that what we smell,

175
0:07:35.93,000 --> 0:07:37,000
we each smell a completely different world.

176
0:07:38.789,000 --> 0:07:39,000
Now, smell was the hardest

177
0:07:40.498,000 --> 0:07:41,000
of the senses to crack,

178
0:07:42.359,000 --> 0:07:43,000
and the Nobel Prize awarded to

179
0:07:44.074,000 --> 0:07:45,000
Richard Axel and Linda Buck

180
0:07:45.707,000 --> 0:07:47,000
was only awarded in 2004

181
0:07:48.14,000 --> 0:07:5,000
for their discovery of how smell works.

182
0:07:50.93,000 --> 0:07:51,000
It's really hard,

183
0:07:52.307,000 --> 0:07:54,000
but in essence, nerves from the brain

184
0:07:54.898,000 --> 0:07:56,000
go up into the nose

185
0:07:57.111,000 --> 0:07:59,000
and on these nerves exposed in the nose

186
0:07:59.492,000 --> 0:08:02,000
to the outside air are receptors,

187
0:08:02.546,000 --> 0:08:05,000
and odor molecules coming in on a sniff

188
0:08:05.695,000 --> 0:08:07,000
interact with these receptors,

189
0:08:07.845,000 --> 0:08:11,000
and if they bond, they send the nerve a signal

190
0:08:12.104,000 --> 0:08:14,000
which goes back into the brain.

191
0:08:14.412,000 --> 0:08:16,000
